Mountain lion attempts a grab and go on a small dog.

If the dangers of leaving your pets outside in an area known for cougars wasn't already apparent, this will hopefully illustrate just how easily they can gain access to your beloved pets.

Mountain lions hunt primarily by sight, so the first thing I would change about this enclosure (I'm making the assumption that it is fully enclosed) would be to eliminate or block up any gate or fencing that the cougar can acquire a target through.

This will not stop an encounter like this entirely, but it would significantly lower the chances of a cougar testing his luck if he has to take extra steps to see inside.

Predators like the cougar are textbook opportunists, the meal that presents the least amount of challenge is the one they prefer - so making your pets look like a challenge to grab is one of the best ways to keep them around.

Luckily, this encounter ended with a few shaken up dogs, a frantic owner and an unsuccessful cougar.

I made this big boy, and everything else in the piece, without any references at all. It was such a fun challenge! Please ignore an errors since I'm not much if a writer, but here's a bit of the meaning behind why this piece was made:
.
.
ü¶ÑüåàüíñUnicorns are being used in my work as a symbolic animal of happiness, calm, and transformation that I thought was as impossible as the existence of unicorns for me. I was recently diagnosed, and started medication for, bipolar disorder, ADHD, and OCD. I am drawing less serious subjects and pieces as my brain adjusts. I started drawing the first unicorn when I made my first psychiatrist appointment, and started drawing the "Alicorn" piece for this exhibition on the day I was officially diagnosed. Since I am feeling mentally "lighter", I finally started experimenting again. "Alicorn" was a perfect challenge during this adjustment period because the entire piece was made up from my anatomical memory. Not a single reference was used for anything in the drawing. The actual concept of the piece is my love of wanting to draw unicorns fighting demons. Good old "good vs. evil". In this piece, the winged unicorn (also called an alicorn apparently) is slaying a little dragon. Both are going to appear a lot more this year, as well as other fantastical creatures, as my psychiatrist and I perfect my treatments.
.

Yesterday when I read about the passing of Juan Gimenez, I grabbed the collection of "The Metabarons" that I offered to Whitney years ago. I remember giving it to her and presenting it as some kind of "When you read this, you will understand bits and pieces of your husband that can not be explained otherwise". With the Metabarons, Jodo and Gimenez made me, somehow. They heavily participated to my small effort at self-building, as a child.
When some kids were reading books about red toy cars and elephants going to school, I was going through the beautiful tales of mutilation, violence and sex. Flesh, blood and mechanical steel. 
Removed eyes and teared up wombs.

The poetry of violence, the mysticism of madness, the intensity of tragedy, they never left me. 
As a son of that beautifully fucked-up creative couple that were Gimenez and Jodorowsky, I join the cortege of artists and readers who have a thing to say about death today.

MY TOP 5 GRAZING TABLE TIPS üçá‚ú® I swear every table I set up I learn something more! I hope these tips help if a large set up seems daunting!!
-
1) Lay your base!‚ú®üí™I use parchment paper as the base under every table, this helps for easy clean up and ensures a safe space for placing all your ingredients! Laying parchment paper also helps me get a visual for the size and shape of of the table will come together!
-
2) Add your props FIRST!‚ú®üçΩBefore I add any food I lay out where my bowls, cheese boards and any plates will go! Again this helps me visualize the final product as I begin to create!
-
3) Get your grape on!‚ú®üçáAdding the big beautiful bunches of grapes right away is a great way to start adding colour to your table and take up lots of space making filling in the table less overwhelming!
-
4) After the grapes I add all my dry goods!‚ú® ü•® I start placing rows of crackers and fill in blank spaces with larger items like granola bites, protein balls and dried mango. I always start with dry goods so I don‚Äôt worry about the fresh ingredients sitting out while I create!
-
5) Work with your environment!‚ú®üåøI never really know how the table will look until it‚Äôs done!! I like to create with the vibes and colours of the space, it helps the final product look beautifully cohesive with the space!

I didn't have time to nerd out in this video about how cool this machine is‚ùóÔ∏è
So here's what really excited me: 
The Tonal uses electromagnetic based tension to provide resistance AKA weight üß≤. Not only is the weight adjustable on the touch screen but you can turn the weight on & off on the handle accessories - this was a big factor for me, on top of the fact that the arms can be positioned just about anywhere which means I have tons of movement options for every muscle group I train. 
Take back squats, for example, either end of the barbell attachment is connected on each arm, both just above the ground; it wouldn't be fun to huck 200 lbs of weight from there to my back. Don‚Äôt worry, no need for a squat rack because I simply turn the weight resistance 'off', effortlessly place the barbell in position across my shoulders, and turn the resistance 'on' all by clicking a button on the barbell and boom! I've got 200 lbs on my back like that, ready for reps ü¶æ!
FYI for those interested but don't know as much about resistance training ‚û°Ô∏è Tonal has 100's of workout routines with different male & female trainers that instruct you on exactly what to do and they have long term workout programs too. One more neato feature I can't not share - since the machine can detect deceleration in your reps (AKA when you would need a spotter b/c you're struggling) it automatically and incrementally lowers the resistance, allowing you to complete sets and still get a good lift in.
